      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production hardware. Each construct dimensionally inspected prior to testing; all within drawing tolerances. Constructs distributed across two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability. Sample size sufficient for the statistical acceptance metric (E/uval)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two load levels.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single standardized ASTM F1717 load configuration (fixed offset, fixed crosshead speed). Only one test condition evaluated; the required level of 3 demands at least two distinct load conditions to bracket the clinical use space. This factor is below the required level and represents a known gap in the validation evidence; accepted under the overall assessment because model influence is Medium and testing confirms results at the primary load condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs match experimental setup parameters within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA (fixed base, displacement-controlled crosshead at 25 mm/min equivalent quasi-static) replicate the F1717 test fixture configuration. Material inputs drawn from the same MTR lot as tested hardware. Crosshead displacement mapped to applied force via load cell calibration records. No parameter substitutions required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All three QoIs satisfy <10% relative difference criterion AND E/uval < 1.96 for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: FEA 187 N/mm vs. experimental mean 192 N/mm (2.6% difference, E/uval=0.81). Yield force: FEA 412 N vs. experimental mean 421 N (2.1% difference, E/uval=0.74). Force at 40 mm: FEA 638 N vs. experimental mean 651 N (2.0% difference, E/uval=0.69). All QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Validation uncertainty estimated per ASME V&V 40 Section 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the same metrics used in the regulatory submission and are mechanistically linked to clinical failure modes.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are explicitly specified in ASTM F1717 and are the primary metrics used in the 510(k) predicate comparison. Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spine; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are surrogates for fatigue endurance and implant integrity under worst-case loading. QoIs are directly relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same device geometry, material lot, and loading protocol as the COU; any differences are documented and their impact bounded.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs are built from the same production hardware and material lot as the COU device. Loading protocol follows ASTM F1717 which is the regulatory standard for the submission. The single gap (one test condition, see Test conditions factor) is documented; its impact is bounded by the conservative nature of the F1717 worst-case offset. Overall validation activity is judged sufficiently relevant to support the COU."
